│ The root cause is likely incorrect instruction placement, especially when dealing with complex control flow and PHI nodes. The SLP vectorizer must place newly generated vector          │
│ instructions in a basic block that dominates all their uses. Furthermore, all operands of the new instruction must be available (i.e., their definitions must dominate) at the insertion │
│ point.                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The function `BoUpSLP::hoistInsertPoint` in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp` is responsible for ensuring that the insertion point for a new instruction is valid with   │
│ respect to its operands. It iterates through the operands and, if an operand is not available at the current insertion point, it "hoists" the insertion point to a common dominator.     │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I've identified a potential flaw in this function's handling of PHI node operands. The code has a special case for `PHINode`:                                                            │
