│       InsertBlock = DT.findNearestCommonDominator(InsertBlock, PN->getParent());                                                                                                         │
│       continue;                                                                                                                                                                          │
│     }                                                                                                                                                                                    │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
│ This logic is incorrect. The value of a PHI node is defined within its parent basic block and is available in all blocks dominated by it. By finding a common dominator of the current   │
│ `InsertBlock` and the PHI's parent block (`PN->getParent()`), the insertion point might be moved "up" the dominator tree to a block that is no longer dominated by `PN->getParent()`.    │
│ This would make the PHI's value unavailable at the insertion point, leading to invalid IR.                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
